RAJESH KUMAR
n New Delhi
In a move to check rampant
online fraud, the Union
Cabinet on Tuesday
approved the much-awaited
Online Gaming Bill, which
seeks to regulate the misuse
of online gaming apps and
similar platforms. Titled ‘The
Promotion and Regulation of
Online Gaming Bill, 2025’,
the proposal law aims to
regulate the sector and curb
illegal betting. The Bill is
likely to be tabled in
Parliament on Wednesday.
The move of the Government
comes after a rise in fraud
cases in recent months, with
several investigating agen-
cies stepping up action
against celebrities promoting
such applications.
The Bill proposes that any
person offering online
money gaming service in
violation of the stipulated

cies stepping up action
against celebrities promoting
such applications.
The Bill proposes that any
person offering online
money gaming service in
violation of the stipulated
provisions will face imprison-
ment of up to three years or
a fine that may extend to `1
crore, or both. The provi-
sions also stipulate imprison-
ment of up to two years and
or a fine of up to `50 lakh, or
both, for those indulging in
advertisements in contra-
vention of rules. Also, those
engaging in any transaction
or authorisation of funds
will be liable for up to three
years imprisonment, or a
fine up to `1 crore or both,
according to the source. 
Repeat offences for viola-
tion related to online money
gaming attracts higher strin-
gent jail term (3-5 years) as
well as fine.
New e-gaming Bill to ban real money games

n New Delhi
In a significant diplomatic
outreach ahead of the
Shanghai Cooperation
Organisation (SCO) Summit,
Chinese Foreign Minister
Wang Yi met with Prime
Minister Narendra Modi in
New Delhi on Tuesday. The
meeting marks a continua-
tion of efforts by both
nations to stabilise and
improve ties following
recent signs of a thaw in
India-China relations.
Wang Yi’s visit comes just
days before the SCO Summit,
scheduled to be held in
Tianjin on August 31 and
September 1, which PM Modi
is confirmed to attend.
Reflecting on the positive
trajectory of bilateral ties, PM
Modi posted on X, “Since my
meeting with President Xi in
Kazan last year, India-China
relations have made steady
progress guided by respect
for each other’s interests
and sensitivities. I look
forward to our next meeting
in Tianjin on the sidelines of
the SCO Summit. Stable, pre-
dictable, constructive ties
between India and China
will contribute significantly
to regional as well as global

forward to our next meeting

dictable, constructive ties

will contribute significantly
to regional as well as global
peace and prosperity.”

The National Council of
Educational Research and
Training ( NCERT) has intro-
duced two modules on the
Operation Sindoor for classes 3
to 12 describing the mission not
just as a military operation but
a promise to protect peace
and honour the lives lost in the
Pahalgam terror attack. 
The modules which have
been introduced as supple-
mentary material in the cur-
riculum come over three
months after Operation
Sindoor. The modules also
state that although Pakistan
denied any involvement in
the Pahalgam terror attack, it
was carried out on “direct
orders” by “Pakistan’s mili-
tary and political leadership”.
“India launched missiles
and air strikes, targeting nine
terrorist sites situated in

on May 7, 2025. Out of nine

destroyed by the Indian Army,
while the Indian Air Force
destroyed terrorist targets in
Muridke and Bahawalpur,
which are the nerve centres of

former Supreme Court judge
and the first Lokayukta of
Goa, B Sudershan Reddy, as

contest has emerged as a
“south versus south”. NDA

hails from Tamil Nadu while
Sudershan Reddy is from
Telangana.  The vice presi-
dential contest is now billed
as an ideological battle by
the INDIA bloc, as numbers
favour the ruling BJP-led
alliance.

Mallikarjun Kharge

out a joint statement of the
Opposition parties, Kharge,
who is the Leader of the
Opposition in Rajya Sabha,
said Reddy is one of India’s
most “distinguished and
progressive jurists”. The
INDIA bloc’s decision,
announced by Congress
chief Mallikarjun Kharge,
comes after several rounds
of discussion during which
Opposition leaders brain-
stormed about names
acceptable to all parties in
the bloc. 
The Opposition’s move to
force a contest is largely an
optics game to ensure that
the BJP does not get a
walkover. A contest,
however tilted, will provide
the Opposition to showcase
its unity at a time when it is
pushing hard to corner the
Government on the issue of
alleged poll irregularities.

SC SLAMS CFSL IN
MANIPUR CASE
The Supreme Court criticized
the Central Forensic Science
Laboratory (CFSL) for
misinterpreting its direction
regarding leaked audio clips
allegedly involving former
Manipur CM N. Biren Singh
in the 2023 ethnic violence.
The Court clarified it sought
voice matching with Singh's
known samples, not video
authenticity. It rejected
Singh's daughter's plea to
join the case and expressed
frustration over vague
responses from CFSL.
Petitioner KOHUR,
represented by Prashant
Bhushan, demanded a
court-monitored SIT probe,
alleging Singh's involvement
in instigating violence. The
case, involving over 260
deaths and widespread
displacement, will be heard
next on August 25.

New Delhi: During high-level talks held in New Delhi, the
Chinese delegation led by Foreign Minister Wang Yi raised the
issue of Taiwan. Responding to the remarks, the Indian side
firmly reaffirmed that its position on Taiwan remains
unchanged. India emphasised that, consistent with the
approach adopted by much of the international community, it
maintains economic, technological and cultural ties with
Taiwan — a practice that will continue. Indian officials further
noted that China itself engages with Taiwan in these same
non-political spheres, highlighting the pragmatic nature of
such interactions. The exchange was part of a broader
diplomatic dialogue ahead of the Shanghai Cooperation

non-political spheres, highlighting the pragmatic nature of
such interactions. The exchange was part of a broader
diplomatic dialogue ahead of the Shanghai Cooperation
Organisation (SCO) Summit in Tianjin, where a wide range of
regional and bilateral issues were discussed.
In an official statement, the Ministry of External Affairs
(MEA) stated, “The Chinese side raised the issue of Taiwan.
The Indian side underlined that there was no change in its
position on this issue. It pointed out that, like the rest of the
world, India had a relationship with Taiwan that focuses on
economic, technological and cultural ties and that this would
continue.”

n Lucknow
Thieves stole jewellery worth
Rs 15.6 lakh and cash from a
house in Gudamba in the
intervening on August 8
night. The miscreants also
took away the LED TV
installed in the house. The
incident came to light on
Tuesday.
The family had gone to
Jammu and the house was
lying closed. The house
owner apprehended the role
of an e-rickshaw driver, who
dropped them at the railway
station, in the theft at his
house.  As per reports, house
owner Sanjeev Kumar of
Shivani Bihar Colony,
Gudamba, along with his

reported to the Shah Commission. The Shah Commission
Report was tabled in Parliament on August 31, 1978,” the
minister said.

It is the same old story. Every year monsoon is awaited
eagerly as a lot depends upon it — water to irrigate fields,
replenish drinking water supply, relief from summer heat
and recharging the water table — but when it arrives it also
brings with it misery and hardships — the downpour cause
floods which in turn cause loss of life and property,
dislocation of people and disease. As the climate-change is
getting more and more pronounced, monsoon is getting
erratic, unpredictable and more deadly. This year it has
been rather harsh. Torrential rains, floods, and cloudbursts
have left hundreds dead, thousands displaced, and several
states reeling under nature’s fury.
Himachal Pradesh has been the worst hit, with over 260

basins are swelling dangerously, while the hilly states

Jan Vishwas bill progress
The Jan Vishwas (Amendment Bill) 2025 marks a signif-
icant milestone in India’s regulatory reform journey. It
reflects the Government’s principle of “Maximum
Government, Minimum Governance” and is expected
to catalyse sustainable economic growth and improved
ease of doing business. The bill seeks to decriminalise
as many as 288 provisions relating to minor offences
under various laws, aiming to promote ease of living
and improve the business climate. 
Twenty amendments are proposed under the Motor
Vehicles Act to ease compliance for citizens. The
current fine of up to `500 for breach of state Government
rules is substituted with a fixed penalty of the same
amount. The proposed amendment also introduces a

current fine of up to `500 for breach of state Government
rules is substituted with a fixed penalty of the same
amount. The proposed amendment also introduces a
provision for an automatic 10 per cent increase of fines
and penalties every three years to maintain deterrence
without requiring fresh legislative amendments. Most
importantly, Jan Vishwas 2.0 intends to usher in com-
prehensive reforms to unburden the judiciary, reduc-
ing litigation, time, and costs.  Amendments in the NDMC
Act and MSME Development Act further enhance trust-
based governance. If passed, these reforms will
improve ease of doing business and strengthen confi-
dence in India’s regulatory environment.

need to declare it, and pay any duty. Women do it with
designer bags, and gold or diamond jewellery. The smart
ones cover them up with shawls, sweaters or jackets.
Since there are no tags, no invoices, and people are
wearing or carrying the items, it is difficult for the

if they find a legal technicality.

whose gold bangles were confiscated by the Customs.

A year ago, this is what happened with a woman,
whose gold bangles were confiscated by the Customs.
When the owner explained that they were a part of
personal jewellery, which she was possibly wearing
when she left the country, the officials refused to accept
it. They claimed that the purity of the gold was too high,
about 24-karat, which is used for commercial purposes.
Jewellery is generally made from 22-karat or lower
purity gold. In the minds of the Customs, it was a clear
case of importing high-purity gold without paying
duties, with the aim to sell it in the open market at
higher prices.
After reforms and liberalisation, gold smuggling
declined. The criminals in the Middle East, which
supplied most of the gold, were forced to seek
alternatives. However, human couriers, who carried
gold, or wore them, continued to operate because of the
seemingly-lucrative price differential between the
global and Indian prices. The Customs is aware of it, and

global and Indian prices. The Customs is aware of it, and
has seized huge quantities of gold at the Indian airports.
The officials know that even normal people do it. They
carry gold as personal items to escape the duties. In the
woman’s case, the officers felt that they found a
genuine, albeit technical, reason to confiscate the gold
bangles. The woman went to the court.
The Delhi High Court ruled in the woman’s favour. It
stated that the purity of gold cannot be the reason to
determine if the bangles were personal or not. It is an
individual’s choice to opt for 22-karat or 24-karat gold.
The Customs needs to prove that the bangles were
meant for commercial sale, and did not belong to the
woman. Legally, there needs to be a distinction between
personal and commercial use. In this case, the Customs
had to establish that the bangles were purchased

woman. Legally, there needs to be a distinction between
personal and commercial use. In this case, the Customs
had to establish that the bangles were purchased
abroad, and the woman was not wearing them when she
left the country. The make of the jewellery, nature of
gold and design can offer evidence. But in this case,
none of it was presented to the court by the Customs.
Lawyers agree that although the practice of bringing
high-value items as personal ones is common among
Indian travellers, the Customs needs to prove it. There
are more genuine passengers, who legitimately wear
and carry personal items. Hence, it is imperative to
pinpoint the illegal carriers or couriers. This requires
adequate evidence, and application of the mind. Mere
suspicion or legal technicalities related to gold purity
are not enough.
